		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>How to convert a photo to NES format</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />How to import realistic graphics into an NES game<br /><br />I couldn't find a good tutorial on this, so I'm going to write it myself<br /><br />I use Photoshop 5.5 (sorry, it's old)<br />-hold control, and click (=delete) all the swatches<br />-create 4 new swatches, white/lt gray/dk gray/black<br />-click the little arrow, save swatches as &quot;4color.aco&quot;<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/gtzh6cg73l932qa/howto1.jpg">http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/gtzh ... howto1.jpg</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Open your photo<br />-select the part you want, and crop it.<br />-click image/image size, change to a realistic NES size...32x32, 16x16<br />-click image/adjust/curves, and draw 4 flat lines - this is the tricky part, <br />because final result will depend on exactly how you draw those lines.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/ebuek7sl919zx3j/howto2.jpg">http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/ebue ... howto2.jpg</a><!-- m --><br /><br />-at this point I touched it up slightly with the pencil tool<br />-click image/mode/indexed color<br />-click palette &quot;custom&quot;, table &quot;custom&quot;, load...<br /> then find your 4color.aco file<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/2jh46neavala7qu/howto3.jpg">http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/2jh4 ... howto3.jpg</a><!-- m --><br /><br />-click select/all, edit/copy<br /><br />Open YY-CHR, New File...<br />-click edit/paste<br />-then touch up the picture, and save it.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/9y75zcx045xqhy8/howto4.jpg">http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/9y75 ... howto4.jpg</a><!-- m --><br /><br />You may have to adjust brightness after the &quot;curves&quot; step to get better <br />results with the index color step. All these examples are 32 pixels wide.<br /><br />Here's a soccer ball (football), for another example.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/zpfh6pvoesaymea/howto5.jpg">http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/zpfh ... howto5.jpg</a><!-- m -->

		

		</td>
	</tr>
